{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14949"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.04,0.02,0.24,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring inflammation, new blood vessels form but remain leaky until endothelial cells mature and form proper intercellular junctions. This results in plasma proteins moving from the intravascular space into the surrounding tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the resulting changes in osmotic pressures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lower intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure","Higher intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure","Lower intravascular and lower interstitial osmotic pressure","Higher intravascular and lower interstitial osmotic pressure","Unchanged intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen plasma proteins leak from immature blood vessels during inflammation, two key changes occur: the intravascular osmotic pressure decreases due to loss of proteins from the blood, whilst the interstitial osmotic pressure increases as these proteins accumulate in the tissue spaces. This creates an osmotic gradient that draws fluid out of the vessels into the interstitial space, contributing to inflammatory edema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELower intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes both changes that occur when proteins leak from blood vessels into tissues. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigher intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests that protein loss would increase intravascular osmotic pressure. \u003Cstrong\u003ELower intravascular and lower interstitial osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E fails to account for protein accumulation in the interstitial space. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigher intravascular and lower interstitial osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E describes the opposite of what actually occurs during protein leakage. \u003Cstrong\u003EUnchanged intravascular and higher interstitial osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E ignores the decrease in intravascular osmotic pressure that results from protein loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During inflammation, protein leakage from immature blood vessels decreases intravascular osmotic pressure while increasing interstitial fluid osmotic pressure.","Changes in osmotic pressure gradients drive fluid movement from blood vessels into tissues, contributing to inflammatory edema."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Punchard NA, Whelan CJ, Adcock I. The Journal of Inflammation. J Inflamm (Lond). 2004 Sep 27;1(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1476-9255-1-1. PMID: 15813979; PMCID: PMC1074343","Margraf A, Lowell CA, Zarbock A. Neutrophils in acute inflammation: current concepts and translational implications. Blood. 2022 Apr 7;139(14):2130-2144. doi: 10.1182/blood.2021012295. PMID: 34624098; PMCID: PMC9728535","Odunayo, A.. Albumin and colloid osmotic pressure. 2016. Monitoring and Intervention for the Critically Ill Small Animal: The Rule of 20, 43-53. https://doi.org/10.1002/9781118923870.ch4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97409"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T15:57:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T15:58:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7637"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115406"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"